<h3>3.2 Custom Audiences Applications</h3>
<p>Custom Audiences are critical for improving conversion efficiency:</p>
<p><strong>User Data Import</strong>:<br />
- Website visitors (within 180 days)<br />
- App active users<br />
- Existing customer CRM data<br />
- Cross-platform data from Instagram/Facebook</p>
<p><strong>Lookalike Expansion</strong>:<br />
- Set similarity percentage at <strong>1%-3%</strong> to balance scale and precision<br />
- Prioritize high-value users (e.g., repeat purchasers) as seed data</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Practical Example</strong>: A fast fashion DTC website created Custom Audiences from website visitors with 1% Lookalike expansion, boosting CTR to 1.8x industry average and reducing CPA by 28%.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3>3.3 Interest and Behavior Targeting</h3>
<p>TikTok's interest categories are relatively broad. Adopt a <strong>"Interest + Behavior Combination" strategy</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Interest Tags</strong>: Select 1-2 core interest categories related to your product</li>
<li><strong>Behavior Targeting</strong>: Enable "Recently Active" to reach users with recent interactions</li>
<li><strong>TikTok-Native Behaviors</strong>: Can overlay细分标签 like "recent video viewing history" or "used shopping features"</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h2>IV. Creative Production: Maximizing UGC Style</h2>
<h3>4.1 Core Characteristics of TikTok-Native Creatives</h3>
<p>TikTok users naturally identify advertisements. <strong>Pure branded hard-sell creatives typically achieve less than 15% completion rates</strong>. Successful TikTok ad creatives require:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Authenticity</strong>: Real people, conversational tone, slightly "rough" production style</li>
<li><strong>Entertainment</strong>: Strong hook in first 3 seconds creating suspense or conflict</li>
<li><strong>Brevity</strong>: Deliver core value within first 5 seconds; main video 15-30 seconds</li>
<li><strong>Localization</strong>: Use local language and trending memes from target markets</li>
</ol>
<h3>4.2 High-Converting Creative Structure Breakdown</h3>
<p>Effective TikTok ad creatives typically follow a <strong>"Hook-Problem-Solution-CTA" four-act structure</strong>:</p>
<p><strong>① Hook (0-3 seconds)</strong>: Create visual impact or cognitive conflict<br />
- Wrong: "Our product is great!"<br />
- Right: "POV: You're still paying $50 for this..."</p>
<p><strong>② Problem (4-8 seconds)</strong>: Define user pain points<br />
- Describe real-world frustrations to trigger resonance</p>
<p><strong>③ Solution (9-20 seconds)</strong>: Show how product solves problems<br />
- Highlight core selling points with before/after comparisons<br />
- Include user testimonials or data-backed claims</p>
<p><strong>④ CTA (21-30 seconds)</strong>: Clear call-to-action<br />
- "Tap the link now" / "Use code XXX for 20% off"</p>
<h3>4.3 Creative Testing Matrix Strategy</h3>
<p>Don't concentrate all budget on single creatives. Build a <strong>"3×3 Testing Matrix"</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>3 Creative Types</strong>: Real-person, product showcase, UGC-style (1 each)</li>
<li><strong>3 Different Hooks</strong>: Question-based, number-based, contrast-based (1 each)</li>
<li>Set budget at <strong>$50-100/day</strong> per group; retain Top 1 performer after 48 hours</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Data Reference</strong>: Based on A/B testing across multiple overseas brands, applying this matrix boosted average CTR by <strong>110%-150%</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
